<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Service (1995 through 1999) - SECTION 5: ROCKER ARM ASSEMBLY, CAMSHAFT
        ASSEMBLY, TAPPETS AND PUSH RODS - CAMSHAFT GEAR AND CAMSHAFT
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>CAMSHAFT GEAR AND CAMSHAFT</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="6">
            <title>REMOVAL</title>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">Refer to the appropriate manual sections for removal instructions for fuel,
                    turbocharger, cylinder head and front cover items.
                </emph>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove roller tappets and roller tappet guides from their bores. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600517">5.17</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Mark the tappets as to location in the crankcase, so they can be returned to their
                            original position.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600518">5.18</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    , for location of gears and timing marks. Rotate the engine so that timing marks on lower and upper
                    idler gears, crankshaft and camshaft gears are aligned.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>PRIOR TO REMOVING ANY GEAR, MOUNT A MAGNETIC BASE DIAL INDICATOR ONTO THE ENGINE AND CHECK
                            FOR GEAR BACKLASH AND END PLAY. REFER TO SECTION 8, "TIMING GEAR TRAIN AND FRONT COVER" FOR
                            INSTRUCTION.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1600517" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5167" filename="../figeg5/EG5167.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 5.17 Removing Roller Tappet Guides</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600518" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5313" filename="../figeg5/EG5313.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 5.18 Gears And Timing Marks</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">1. Camshaft Gear</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">2. Upper Idler Gear</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">3. Crankshaft Gear</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">4. Lower Idler Gear</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the high pressure pump as outlined in Section 12,
                    <emph type="bold">"HIGH PRESSURE LUBE OIL SYSTEM"</emph>.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If removing the
                    <emph type="underscr">CAMSHAFT GEAR ONLY</emph>
                    use the following instructions:
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Do not pry on timing disk plate.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the three (3) screws securing the timing disk plate to the camshaft gear.
                        Remove the timing disk plate (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600519">5.19</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install camshaft gear puller
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE4229</emph>to camgear.
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="underscr">DO NOT</emph>
                                USE AN IMPACT WRENCH. USE OF AN IMPACT WRENCH WILL FORCE THE CAMSHAFT TO MOVE REARWARD,
                                RESULTING IN EXCESS CAMSHAFT END PLAY.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Turn the camshaft gear puller. When the camgear has moved out approximately 13 mm
                        (1/2 in.), use a pry bar or ratchet to force the camshaft gear to its forward most position.
                        Finish removing camshaft gear (
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600520">5.20</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        ).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1600519" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg5311" filename="../figeg5/EG5311.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5.19 Removing Timing Disk Plate</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">1. Camshaft Gear</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">2. Timing Disk Plate Mounting Bolts</callout1>
                            <callout1 type="arabic">3. Timing Disk Plate</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1600520" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg5325" filename="../figeg5/EG5325.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 5.20 Moving Camshaft Gear To Forward Position</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">IF REMOVING THE CAMSHAFT GEAR AND CAMSHAFT AS IN ASSEMBLY</emph>, remove two (2)
                    camshaft gear thrust plate bolts. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600521">5.21</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>When the engine is mounted in a turnover stand, rotate engine so front of engine is facing
                            up (engine in vertical position). This position allows for easy removal of camshaft
                            assembly.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the camshaft from the crankcase by lifting the assembly straight up. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600522">5.22</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>This method reduces the risk of damaging the camshaft journals and/or bushings.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1600521" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5324" filename="../figeg5/EG5324.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 5.21 Removing Camshaft Gear Thrust Plate Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600522" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5326" filename="../figeg5/EG5326.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 5.22 Removing Camshaft And Gear From Crankcase</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
